  "local_port": 33206,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the nicest library at Columbia to work at?",
  "response": "Columbia University boasts a variety of exceptional libraries, each with its own unique atmosphere, resources, and amenities. The \"nicest\" library to work at can depend on your specific needs, preferences, and the type of environment you thrive in. Here are some of the top libraries at Columbia that are highly regarded for their work environments:\n\n### 1. **Butler Library**\n- **Overview:** As the flagship library of Columbia University, Butler Library is a central hub for students and faculty. It offers extensive collections, advanced research facilities, and a vibrant academic atmosphere.\n- **Highlights:**\n  - **Spaces:** Multiple reading rooms, quiet study areas, collaborative spaces, and technology-equipped rooms.\n  - **Amenities:** Caf\u00e9, lounges, computer labs, and printing services.\n  - **Ambiance:** Historic architecture combined with modern facilities, providing both inspiration and functionality.\n\n### 2. **Avery Architectural & Fine Arts Library**\n- **Overview:** Ideal for those interested in architecture, art history, and design. Avery Library is renowned for its specialized collections and visually stimulating environment.\n- **Highlights:**\n  - **Collections:** Extensive archives of architectural drawings, photographs, and art books.\n  - **Spaces:** Bright, open areas with ample natural light, specialized studios, and exhibition spaces.\n  - **Ambiance:** Creative and inspiring, perfect for visual thinkers and designers.\n\n### 3. **Rare Book & Manuscript Library (RBML)**\n- **Overview:** RBML is perfect for those who appreciate historical texts, rare manuscripts, and specialized research materials.\n- **Highlights:**\n  - **Collections:** Rare books, manuscripts, maps, and archives spanning various disciplines.\n  - **Spaces:** Quiet, contemplative environments with excellent natural lighting and historic charm.\n  - **Ambiance:** Serene and scholarly, ideal for focused research and exploration of unique materials.\n\n### 4. **C.V. Starr East Asian Library**\n- **Overview:** Specialized in East Asian studies, this library is a great workplace for those interested in Asian languages, history, and culture.\n- **Highlights:**\n  - **Collections:** Comprehensive resources in Chinese, Japanese, Korean, and other East Asian languages.\n  - **Spaces:** Comfortable seating, quiet study areas, and collaborative workspaces.\n  - **Ambiance:** Culturally enriching environment that fosters specialized research and learning.\n\n### 5. **Gargoyle Life Sciences Library**\n- **Overview:** Catering to the life sciences community, this library is ideal for those involved in biology, medicine, and related fields.\n- **Highlights:**\n  - **Resources:** Extensive scientific journals, databases, and research tools.\n  - **Spaces:** Modern study areas, group workrooms, and access to laboratory resources.\n  - **Ambiance:** Dynamic and resource-rich, supporting both individual and collaborative scientific work.\n\n### Choosing the Best Fit for You\n\nWhen determining which library is the nicest to work at, consider the following factors:\n\n- **Purpose:** Are you conducting specialized research, needing quiet study spaces, or looking for collaborative environments?\n- **Atmosphere:** Do you prefer a historic and serene setting or a modern and vibrant workspace?\n- **Resources:** Which library offers the materials and technological support you require?\n- **Amenities:** Consider available amenities like caf\u00e9s, lounges, and study rooms that enhance your working experience.\n\n**Butler Library** is often considered the most versatile and centrally located, making it a popular choice for many. However, if your work aligns more closely with a specialized field, libraries like Avery, RBML, or the C.V. Starr East Asian Library might offer a more tailored and pleasant working environment.\n\nUltimately, the nicest library for you will depend on your personal preferences and specific academic or research needs. It might be beneficial to visit a few of these libraries to get a feel for their environments and determine which one best suits your work style.",
